1 of information or the method of circumstances of preparation indicate lack of trustworthiness. The
2 term “business” as used in this subsection includes business, institution, association, profession, oc-
3 cupation, and calling of every kind, whether or not conducted for profit.
4 (7) Evidence that a matter is not included in the memoranda, reports, records, or data compila-
5 tions, and in any form, kept in accordance with the provisions of subsection (6) of this section, to
6 prove the nonoccurrence or nonexistence of the matter, if the matter was of a kind of which a
7 memorandum, report, record, or data compilation was regularly made and preserved, unless the
8 sources of information or other circumstances indicate lack of trustworthiness.
9 (8) Records, reports, statements or data compilations, in any form, of public offices or agencies,
10 including federally recognized American Indian tribal governments, setting forth:
11 (a) The activities of the office or agency;
12 (b) Matters observed pursuant to duty imposed by law as to which matters there was a duty to
13 report, excluding, in criminal cases, matters observed by police officers and other law enforcement
14 personnel;
15 (c) In civil actions and proceedings and against the government in criminal cases, factual
16 findings, resulting from an investigation made pursuant to authority granted by law, unless the
17 sources of information or other circumstances indicate lack of trustworthiness; or
18 (d) In civil actions and criminal proceedings, a sheriff’s return of service.
19 (9) Records or data compilations, in any form, of births, fetal deaths, deaths or marriages, if the
20 report thereof was made to a public office, including a federally recognized American Indian tribal
21 government, pursuant to requirements of law.
22 (10) To prove the absence of a record, report, statement or data compilation, in any form, or the
23 nonoccurrence or nonexistence of a matter of which a record, report, statement or data compilation,
24 in any form, was regularly made and preserved by a public office or agency, including a federally
25 recognized American Indian tribal government, evidence in the form of a certification in accordance
26 with ORS 40.510, or testimony, that diligent search failed to disclose the record, report, statement
27 or data compilation, or entry.
28 (11) Statements of births, marriages, divorces, deaths, legitimacy, ancestry, relationship by blood
29 or marriage, or other similar facts of personal or family history, contained in a regularly kept record
30 of a religious organization.
31 (12) A statement of fact contained in a certificate that the maker performed a marriage or other
32 ceremony or administered a sacrament, made by a member of the clergy, a public official, an official
33 of a federally recognized American Indian tribal government or any other person authorized by the
34 rules or practices of a religious organization or by law to perform the act certified, and purporting
35 to have been issued at the time of the act or within a reasonable time thereafter.
36 (13) Statements of facts concerning personal or family history contained in family bibles,
37 genealogies, charts, engravings on rings, inscriptions on family portraits, engravings on urns, crypts,
38 or tombstones, or the like.
39 (14) The record of a document purporting to establish or affect an interest in property, as proof
40 of content of the original recorded document and its execution and delivery by each person by whom
41 it purports to have been executed, if the record is a record of a public office, including a federally
42 recognized American Indian tribal government, and an applicable statute authorizes the recording
43 of documents of that kind in that office.
44 (15) A statement contained in a document purporting to establish or affect an interest in prop-
45 erty if the matter stated was relevant to the purpose of the document, unless dealings with the
[2]

HB 4157
1 property since the document was made have been inconsistent with the truth of the statement or
2 the purport of the document.
3 (16) Statements in a document in existence 20 years or more the authenticity of which is es-
4 tablished.
5 (17) Market quotations, tabulations, lists, directories, or other published compilations, generally
6 used and relied upon by the public or by persons in particular occupations.
7 (18) (Reserved.)
8 (18a)(a) A complaint of sexual misconduct, complaint of abuse as defined in ORS 107.705 or
9 419B.005, complaint of abuse of an elderly person, as those terms are defined in ORS 124.050, or a
10 complaint relating to a violation of ORS 163.205 or 164.015 in which a person 65 years of age or
11 older is the victim, made by the witness after the commission of the alleged misconduct or abuse
12 at issue. Except as provided in paragraph (b) of this subsection, such evidence must be confined to
13 the fact that the complaint was made.
14 (b) A statement made by a person concerning an act of abuse as defined in ORS 107.705 or
15 419B.005, a statement made by a person concerning an act of abuse of an elderly person, as those
16 terms are defined in ORS 124.050, or a statement made by a person concerning a violation of ORS
17 163.205 or 164.015 in which a person 65 years of age or older is the victim, is not excluded by ORS
18 40.455 if the declarant either testifies at the proceeding and is subject to cross-examination, or is
19 unavailable as a witness but was chronologically or mentally under 12 years of age when the
20 statement was made or was 65 years of age or older when the statement was made. However, if a
21 declarant is unavailable, the statement may be admitted in evidence only if the proponent estab-
22 lishes that the time, content and circumstances of the statement provide indicia of reliability, and
23 in a criminal trial or juvenile delinquency proceeding that there is corroborative evidence of the
24 act of abuse and of the alleged perpetrator’s opportunity to participate in the conduct and that the
25 statement possesses indicia of reliability as is constitutionally required to be admitted. No statement
26 may be admitted under this paragraph unless the proponent of the statement makes known to the
27 adverse party the proponent’s intention to offer the statement and the particulars of the statement
28 no later than 15 days before trial, except for good cause shown. For purposes of this paragraph, in
29 addition to those situations described in ORS 40.465 (1), the declarant shall be considered “unavail-
30 able” if the declarant has a substantial lack of memory of the subject matter of the statement, is
31 presently incompetent to testify, is unable to communicate about the abuse or sexual conduct be-
32 cause of fear or other similar reason or is substantially likely, as established by expert testimony,
33 to suffer lasting severe emotional trauma from testifying. Unless otherwise agreed by the parties,
34 the court shall examine the declarant in chambers and on the record or outside the presence of the
35 jury and on the record. The examination shall be conducted immediately prior to the commencement
36 of the trial in the presence of the attorney and the legal guardian or other suitable person as des-
37 ignated by the court. If the declarant is found to be unavailable, the court shall then determine the
38 admissibility of the evidence. The determinations shall be appealable under ORS 138.045 (1)(d). The
39 purpose of the examination shall be to aid the court in making its findings regarding the availability
40 of the declarant as a witness and the reliability of the statement of the declarant. In determining
41 whether a statement possesses indicia of reliability under this paragraph, the court may consider,
42 but is not limited to, the following factors:
43 (A) The personal knowledge of the declarant of the event;
44 (B) The age and maturity of the declarant or extent of disability if the declarant is a person
45 with a developmental disability;
[3]

HB 4157
1 (C) Certainty that the statement was made, including the credibility of the person testifying
2 about the statement and any motive the person may have to falsify or distort the statement;
3 (D) Any apparent motive the declarant may have to falsify or distort the event, including bias,
4 corruption or coercion;
5 (E) The timing of the statement of the declarant;
6 (F) Whether more than one person heard the statement;
7 (G) Whether the declarant was suffering pain or distress when making the statement;
8 (H) Whether the declarant’s young age or disability makes it unlikely that the declarant fabri-
9 cated a statement that represents a graphic, detailed account beyond the knowledge and experience
10 of the declarant;
11 (I) Whether the statement has internal consistency or coherence and uses terminology appro-
12 priate to the declarant’s age or to the extent of the declarant’s disability if the declarant is a person
13 with a developmental disability;
14 (J) Whether the statement is spontaneous or directly responsive to questions; and
15 (K) Whether the statement was elicited by leading questions.
16 (c) This subsection applies to all civil, criminal and juvenile proceedings.
17 (d) This subsection applies to a child declarant, a declarant who is an elderly person as defined
18 in ORS 124.050 or an adult declarant with a developmental disability. For the purposes of this sub-
19 section, “developmental disability” means any disability attributable to mental retardation, autism,
20 cerebral palsy, epilepsy or other disabling neurological condition that requires training or support
21 similar to that required by persons with mental retardation, if either of the following apply:
22 (A) The disability originates before the person attains 22 years of age, or if the disability is at-
23 tributable to mental retardation the condition is manifested before the person attains 18 years of
24 age, the disability can be expected to continue indefinitely, and the disability constitutes a sub-
25 stantial handicap to the ability of the person to function in society.
26 (B) The disability results in a significant subaverage general intellectual functioning with con-
27 current deficits in adaptive behavior that are manifested during the developmental period.
28 (19) Reputation among members of a person’s family by blood, adoption or marriage, or among
29 a person’s associates, or in the community, concerning a person’s birth, adoption, marriage, divorce,
30 death, legitimacy, relationship by blood or adoption or marriage, ancestry, or other similar fact of
31 a person’s personal or family history.
32 (20) Reputation in a community, arising before the controversy, as to boundaries of or customs
33 affecting lands in the community, and reputation as to events of general history important to the
34 community or state or nation in which located.
35 (21) Reputation of a person’s character among associates of the person or in the community.
36 (22) Evidence of a final judgment, entered after a trial or upon a plea of guilty, but not upon a
37 plea of no contest, adjudging a person guilty of a crime other than a traffic offense, to prove any
38 fact essential to sustain the judgment, but not including, when offered by the government in a
39 criminal prosecution for purposes other than impeachment, judgments against persons other than the
40 accused. The pendency of an appeal may be shown but does not affect admissibility.
41 (23) Judgments as proof of matters of personal, family or general history, or boundaries, essen-
42 tial to the judgment, if the same would be provable by evidence of reputation.
43 (24) Notwithstanding the limits contained in subsection (18a) of this section, in any proceeding
44 in which a child under 12 years of age at the time of trial, or a person with a developmental disa-
45 bility as described in subsection (18a)(d) of this section, may be called as a witness to testify con-
