1 cerning an act of abuse, as defined in ORS 419B.005, or sexual conduct performed with or on the
2 child or person with a developmental disability by another, the testimony of the child or person with
3 a developmental disability taken by contemporaneous examination and cross-examination in another
4 place under the supervision of the trial judge and communicated to the courtroom by closed-circuit
5 television or other audiovisual means. Testimony will be allowed as provided in this subsection only
6 if the court finds that there is a substantial likelihood, established by expert testimony, that the
7 child or person with a developmental disability will suffer severe emotional or psychological harm
8 if required to testify in open court. If the court makes such a finding, the court, on motion of a
9 party, the child, the person with a developmental disability or the court in a civil proceeding, or on
10 motion of the district attorney, the child or the person with a developmental disability in a criminal
11 or juvenile proceeding, may order that the testimony of the child or the person with a developmental
12 disability be taken as described in this subsection. Only the judge, the attorneys for the parties, the
13 parties, individuals necessary to operate the equipment and any individual the court finds would
14 contribute to the welfare and well-being of the child or person with a developmental disability may
15 be present during the testimony of the child or person with a developmental disability.
16 (25)(a) Any document containing data prepared or recorded by the Oregon State Police pursuant
17 to ORS 813.160 (1)(b)(C) or (E), or pursuant to ORS 475.235 (4), if the document is produced by data
18 retrieval from the Law Enforcement Data System or other computer system maintained and operated
19 by the Oregon State Police, and the person retrieving the data attests that the information was re-
20 trieved directly from the system and that the document accurately reflects the data retrieved.
21 (b) Any document containing data prepared or recorded by the Oregon State Police that is
22 produced by data retrieval from the Law Enforcement Data System or other computer system
23 maintained and operated by the Oregon State Police and that is electronically transmitted through
24 public or private computer networks under an electronic signature adopted by the Oregon State
25 Police if the person receiving the data attests that the document accurately reflects the data re-
26 ceived.
27 (c) Notwithstanding any statute or rule to the contrary, in any criminal case in which docu-
28 ments are introduced under the provisions of this subsection, the defendant may subpoena the ana-
29 lyst, as defined in ORS 475.235 (6), or other person that generated or keeps the original document
30 for the purpose of testifying at the preliminary hearing and trial of the issue. Except as provided
31 in ORS 44.550 to 44.566, no charge shall be made to the defendant for the appearance of the analyst
32 or other person.
33 (26)(a) A statement that purports to narrate, describe, report or explain an incident of domestic
34 violence, as defined in ORS 135.230, made by a victim of the domestic violence within 24 hours after
35 the incident occurred, if the statement:
36 (A) Was recorded, either electronically or in writing, or was made to a peace officer as defined
37 in ORS 161.015, corrections officer, youth correction officer, parole and probation officer, emergency
38 medical services provider or firefighter; and
39 (B) Has sufficient indicia of reliability.
40 (b) In determining whether a statement has sufficient indicia of reliability under paragraph (a)
41 of this subsection, the court shall consider all circumstances surrounding the statement. The court
42 may consider, but is not limited to, the following factors in determining whether a statement has
43 sufficient indicia of reliability:
44 (A) The personal knowledge of the declarant.
45 (B) Whether the statement is corroborated by evidence other than statements that are subject
[5]

HB 4157
1 to admission only pursuant to this subsection.
2 (C) The timing of the statement.
3 (D) Whether the statement was elicited by leading questions.
4 (E) Subsequent statements made by the declarant. Recantation by a declarant is not sufficient
5 reason for denying admission of a statement under this subsection in the absence of other factors
6 indicating unreliability.
7 (27)(a) A statement that purports to narrate, describe, report or explain a crime of
8 trafficking in persons under ORS 163.266, purchasing sex with a minor under ORS 163.413,
9 promoting prostitution under ORS 167.012, compelling prostitution under ORS 167.017, or any
10 attempt, conspiracy or solicitation of a crime listed in this paragraph, that involves a com-
11 mercial sex act as defined in ORS 163.266, if the statement:
12 (A) Was made by a victim of the crime within 24 hours before or after the victim engages
13 in, or offers or agrees to engage in, the commercial sex act;
14 (B) Was recorded, either electronically or in writing, or was made to a peace officer as
15 defined in ORS 161.015, corrections officer, youth correction officer, parole and probation
16 officer, emergency medical services provider or firefighter; and
17 (C) Has sufficient indicia of reliability.
18 (b) In determining whether a statement has sufficient indicia of reliability under para-
19 graph (a) of this subsection, the court shall consider all circumstances surrounding the
20 statement. The court may consider, but is not limited to, the following factors in determining
21 whether a statement has sufficient indicia of reliability:
22 (A) The personal knowledge of the declarant.
23 (B) Whether the statement is corroborated by evidence other than statements that are
24 subject to admission only pursuant to this subsection.
25 (C) The timing of the statement.
26 (D) Whether the statement was elicited by leading questions.
27 (E) Subsequent statements made by the declarant. Recantation by a declarant is not
28 sufficient reason for denying admission of a statement under this subsection in the absence
29 of other factors indicating unreliability.
30 [(27)] (28) A report prepared by a forensic scientist that contains the results of a presumptive
31 test conducted by the forensic scientist as described in ORS 475.235, if the forensic scientist attests
32 that the report accurately reflects the results of the presumptive test.
33 [(28)(a)] (29)(a) A statement not specifically covered by any of the foregoing exceptions but
34 having equivalent circumstantial guarantees of trustworthiness, if the court determines that:
35 (A) The statement is relevant;
36 (B) The statement is more probative on the point for which it is offered than any other evidence
37 that the proponent can procure through reasonable efforts; and
38 (C) The general purposes of the Oregon Evidence Code and the interests of justice will best be
39 served by admission of the statement into evidence.
40 (b) A statement may not be admitted under this subsection unless the proponent of it makes
41 known to the adverse party the intention to offer the statement and the particulars of it, including
42 the name and address of the declarant, sufficiently in advance of the trial or hearing, or as soon as
43 practicable after it becomes apparent that such statement is probative of the issues at hand, to
44 provide the adverse party with a fair opportunity to prepare to meet it.
45 SECTION 2. The amendments to ORS 40.460 by section 1 of this 2026 Act apply to state-
